context: <b5_0>The Reed Dance<b5_0/> today is not an ancient ceremony but a development of <a3_0>the old "umchwasho" custom<a3_0/>. In "umchwasho", <a2_0>all young girls<a2_0/> were placed in a female age-regiment. <a1_0>If any girl became pregnant outside of marriage, her family paid a fine<a1_0/> of one cow to <b6_0>the local chief<b6_0/>. After a number of years, when the <b8_0>girls<b8_0/> had reached a marriageable age, they would perform labour service for the Queen Mother, ending with <a4_0>dancing and feasting<a4_0/>. The country was under <b7_0>the chastity rite of "umchwasho"<b7_0/> until <a0_0>19 August 2005<a0_0/>.
